<subSubSection pageId="27" pageNumber="28" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1436,615,1144]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis box="[151,498,615,640]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,289,615,640]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Diagnosis (</emphasis>
after 
<bibRefCitation author="Butler, T. H." box="[356,487,616,640]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" pagination="1 - 280" refId="ref218371" refString="Butler, T. H. (1980) Shrimps of the Pacific Coast of Canada. Canadian Bulletin of Fisheries and Aquatic Science, 202, 1 - 280." type="journal article" year="1980">Butler1980</bibRefCitation>
).
</emphasis>
Rostrum sharply pointed, angled upward obliquely. Carapace with prominent supraorbital tooth, moderate hepatic spine. Five organs of Pesta present: prominent anterolateral pair, lateral midgastric pair, single posterolateral organ.Antennular peduncle slender. Scaphocerite not reaching end of third segment of antennular peduncle.Second maxilliped short, stout.Third maxilliped barely longer than third pereopod; dactyl of third maxilliped with 8 subsegments. Pereopods slender, pereopod 3 longer than others. Pereopods 4, 5 setose, each without dactyl. Abdominal somites with lateral sulci (difficult to see in preserved material). Telson shorter than uropods, with acute apex. Outer uropod without setae on outer margin. Total length 
<quantity box="[1231,1354,832,856]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.9" metricValueMax="6.1" metricValueMin="5.7" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" unit="mm" value="59.0" valueMax="61.0" valueMin="57.0">57–61 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1436,615,1144]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,356,867,892]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" reason="1">Color in life.</emphasis>
Transparent with orange-red spots over carapace and abdomen, telson, uropods and bases of appendages (
<bibRefCitation author="Butler, T. H." box="[296,434,904,928]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" pagination="1 - 280" refId="ref218371" refString="Butler, T. H. (1980) Shrimps of the Pacific Coast of Canada. Canadian Bulletin of Fisheries and Aquatic Science, 202, 1 - 280." type="journal article" year="1980">Butler 1980</bibRefCitation>
, color plate 1).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1436,615,1144]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,425,939,964]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" reason="1">Habitat and depth.</emphasis>
Pelagic, 
<quantity box="[527,656,940,964]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.225" metricValueMax="2.4" metricValueMin="0.05" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" unit="m" value="1225.0" valueMax="2400.0" valueMin="50.0">50–2400 m</quantity>
, usually above 
<quantity box="[828,915,940,964]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" unit="m" value="1000.0">1000 m</quantity>
, between 
<quantity box="[1027,1153,940,964]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" metricValueMax="6.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" unit="m" value="400.0" valueMax="600.0" valueMin="200.0">200–600 m</quantity>
by day and 
<quantity box="[1288,1401,940,964]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.25" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="0.5" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" unit="m" value="125.0" valueMax="200.0" valueMin="50.0">50–200 m</quantity>
by night.
</paragraph>
